Sister Karen is also an Anglican nun and is a student of Father Silouan.

66
00:06:08,290 --> 00:06:15,677
She used to live very close here, that you might know, down in Bishop's Castle, but has now moved to a glorious place over towards the coast.

67
00:06:17,098 --> 00:06:18,579
And then there's Caroline.

68
00:06:20,362 --> 00:06:27,889
Caroline Jones is a teacher at Gaia House, and for three months of the year, she occupies the position that I had there for four years.

69
00:06:28,223 --> 00:06:37,293
So it's really heartwarming to find somebody here who represents Gaia House and the whole lay tradition of teachers.

70
00:06:38,656 --> 00:06:45,625
So those are our guests.

71
00:06:45,644 --> 00:06:50,571
Well, I delivered it very well, don't you think?

72
00:06:50,591 --> 00:06:53,774
You didn't pay heed to my request.

73
00:06:55,425 --> 00:07:16,117
And now we'd like to invite Bhante Pema Siri to give us a talk, a Dharma talk.

74
00:07:20,670 --> 00:07:23,694
Reverend Bhikkhu Bodhidharma.

75
00:07:23,714 --> 00:07:24,536
Is it?

76
00:07:24,555 --> 00:07:26,918
Yes.

77
00:07:28,360 --> 00:07:28,980
Mahasangha.

78
00:07:32,024 --> 00:07:43,177
Dictators of the various denominations and distinguished guests.

79
00:07:43,276 --> 00:07:46,341
I was asked to

80
00:07:46,725 --> 00:07:59,221
A few words about the meditation by Reverend Bhikkhu Bodhidharma.

81
00:07:59,822 --> 00:08:03,226
Meditation is a very easy thing to perform.

82
00:08:07,651 --> 00:08:14,420
People think that it's a very difficult thing to perform.

83
00:08:14,687 --> 00:08:17,230
It has become difficult because they think it is difficult.

84
00:08:23,660 --> 00:08:27,524
You have certain aims in your life.

85
00:08:30,088 --> 00:08:35,575
So you tend to drop all the main aims in your life at certain times.

86
00:08:38,099 --> 00:08:44,626
So always try to live with not the main aim but the aims that are not

87
00:08:44,894 --> 00:08:45,455
important.

88
00:08:46,576 --> 00:09:05,422
The main aims are that you have to eat, drink, you have to go to toilet, washrooms, you have to sleep, and etc.

89
00:09:05,863 --> 00:09:09,567
These are the main goals of your, aims of your

90
00:09:10,730 --> 00:09:11,110
life.

91
00:09:13,333 --> 00:09:16,457
You can look at these things with wisdom.

92
00:09:17,418 --> 00:09:27,152
So you look at these activities with wisdom.

93
00:09:31,238 --> 00:09:35,082
So you can perform the other balance after that.

94
00:09:36,227 --> 00:09:46,823
So therefore, meditation is not a difficult activity to perform.

95
00:09:47,684 --> 00:09:55,836
A person who lives eight years starts within about 10 minutes.

96
00:09:57,178 --> 00:10:03,567
So if you start 10 minutes a day,

97
00:10:04,408 --> 00:10:09,013
So how long you have been meditating during your time of 80 years?

98
00:10:11,254 --> 00:10:17,581
Almost then, 80 years.

99
00:10:17,721 --> 00:10:33,235
So if you multiply your 8 years into 10 minutes, how long you have been meditating then?

100
00:10:34,884 --> 00:10:41,876
So you have to practice this.

101
00:10:43,860 --> 00:10:53,115
So Bhikkhu Bodhidhamma, Reverend Bhikkhu Bodhidhamma may teach you a better way.

102
00:10:55,419 --> 00:11:00,268
The ten minutes that you are going to stay with meditation or meditate, you have to

103
00:11:01,361 --> 00:11:02,767
Just forget the past.

104
00:11:03,208 --> 00:11:04,011
Give up your past.

105
00:11:05,376 --> 00:11:06,701
You give up your future.

106
00:11:08,047 --> 00:11:12,503
You give up your clinging or the attachment.

107
00:11:12,787 --> 00:11:17,592
You don't keep on thinking or contemplating.

108
00:11:17,972 --> 00:11:21,216
You don't have any hopes or wishes.

109
00:11:23,759 --> 00:11:25,863
You should not perform slowly.

110
00:11:26,562 --> 00:11:37,035
You should not start fast.

111
00:11:38,597 --> 00:11:41,240
So if you can get rid of yourself

112
00:11:41,609 --> 00:11:51,620
with these eight points, so you can reach nibbana soon.

113
00:11:51,660 --> 00:12:10,923
What reverend says,

114
00:12:12,052 --> 00:12:19,645
is to just forget your past, drop your future and try to be in the present.

115
00:12:24,534 --> 00:12:32,610
So time to come, then you can just drop your present also.

116
00:12:32,929 --> 00:12:34,953
There is no present in the world.

117
00:12:37,110 --> 00:12:46,639
That's all.

118
00:12:48,642 --> 00:12:48,881
Yes?

119
00:12:49,081 --> 00:12:50,923
Any question?

120
00:12:50,964 --> 00:12:52,024
No, no.

121
00:12:56,710 --> 00:12:57,711
Brian knows it all.

122
00:12:58,051 --> 00:12:59,832
Oh, absolutely.

123
00:12:59,852 --> 00:13:03,696
And now we'd like Bhante Piyananda to give us a Dharma talk.

124
00:13:04,236 --> 00:13:05,498
Thank you, Bhante.

125
00:13:10,337 --> 00:13:10,759
.

126
00:13:10,778 --> 00:13:11,198
.

127
00:13:11,239 --> 00:13:39,417
.

128
00:13:39,986 --> 00:13:44,394
The incumbent of London .

129
00:13:48,779 --> 00:14:03,361
The sisters.

130
00:14:04,404 --> 00:14:09,850
Members of the various denominations.

131
00:14:10,251 --> 00:14:29,332
Distinguished guests who participate in this ceremony.

132
00:14:30,341 --> 00:14:42,259
I'm very happy to state here for the invitation that you extended to participate at this occasion by the

133
00:14:42,998 --> 00:14:53,493
Bodhidharma and the supporters of this place.

134
00:14:53,572 --> 00:15:11,857
I can remember the day that the foundation stone was laid at this place.

135
00:15:12,562 --> 00:15:38,030
It is obvious that Bhikkhu Bodhidharma had taken a lot of pains to improve this place during the last four years.

136
00:15:41,538 --> 00:15:51,114
He has performed a difficult task in a place where the Buddhism do not exist to that extent.

137
00:15:53,538 --> 00:16:06,600
Today we unveil

138
00:16:07,238 --> 00:16:21,835
a pagoda, which is a very important monument Buddhism is concerned.

139
00:16:22,095 --> 00:16:34,950
Especially countries like Burma, Sri Lanka, the pagoda is revered and given much importance.

140
00:16:36,820 --> 00:17:03,807
The constructing of stupas had taken place with the first visit of Buddha to Sri Lanka.

141
00:17:04,563 --> 00:17:31,380
Later, this became one of the most important sites in Pagodas, sites in the Buddhist viharas.

142
00:17:32,440 --> 00:17:40,569
That is because it symbolizes Buddha, Lord Buddha.

143
00:17:41,230 --> 00:17:59,291
At the latter stage, this was the

144
00:18:00,182 --> 00:18:23,710
This has become a symbol of what you follow up to Nibbana and ultimate goal, the Nibbana.

145
00:18:24,247 --> 00:18:43,169
There are various type of pagodas in these countries.

146
00:18:44,269 --> 00:18:53,240
I will now tell you very concisely.

147
00:18:54,065 --> 00:19:19,211
It is a pagoda in the shape of a heap of grain, in the shape of a bubble, in the shape of a bell, and in the shape of a bell.

148
00:19:20,676 --> 00:19:30,910
Like this, I think Sri Lanka has more importance than any other country in the world.

149
00:19:30,990 --> 00:19:40,522
In particular, Bodhidham Mahamudru, who was our teacher, has explained the pagoda of Unruhan Singh in a new way.

150
00:19:40,542 --> 00:19:44,607
I think he has explained Unruhan Singh in a way that is unique to this country.

151
00:19:45,954 --> 00:19:59,076
The pagoda that Bhikkubodhidham has constructed gives a new version to these pagodas.

152
00:19:59,096 --> 00:20:08,772
.

153
00:20:09,259 --> 00:20:38,592
Because both of them have endeavored to display by the dark circle the buildings who are suffering with avidya or the ignorance.

154
00:20:39,314 --> 00:21:05,372
The white circle, you would have seen the white circle out of the dark circle.

155
00:21:06,262 --> 00:21:27,968
The Bhikkhu Bodhidharma had endeavored to explain, saying, people who have gone forth with the triple gem, and who are with the samadhi here, or the correct view.

156
00:21:29,787 --> 00:21:51,221
After that, you get at the foot of the pagoda, there are three circles that denotes the Buddha, Dhamma, Sangha.

157
00:21:51,893 --> 00:22:18,525
Then you can see

158
00:22:18,724 --> 00:22:22,229
or rather I should call a bell-shaped, am I correct?

159
00:22:22,930 --> 00:22:42,993
A bell-shaped pagoda, which you may find difficult to tread on, and it displays the five, eight noble paths.

160
00:22:43,530 --> 00:22:59,335
If you can tread on this Eight Noble Path, the way that Bhikkhu Bodhidham has displayed, then I have no doubt you can reach Nibbana.

161
00:22:59,634 --> 00:23:09,690
So that is what we unveil today.

162
00:23:10,835 --> 00:23:25,398
So he has established this place.

163
00:23:25,720 --> 00:23:34,934
By that, he

164
00:23:36,198 --> 00:23:43,669
Stability.

165
00:23:44,048 --> 00:23:48,174
Stability.

166
00:23:48,194 --> 00:23:50,798
Yes, stability.

167
00:23:50,818 --> 00:24:05,579
We presume that because Bodhidharma, these endeavours will establish the permanency to this Satipanya retreat centre.

168
00:24:05,678 --> 00:24:30,791
So we all, the Sangha, Maha Sangha, wish that you all live

169
00:24:31,176 --> 00:24:45,682
Peace, prosperity and happiness and that you will ultimately reach the goal that you hope to.

170
00:24:45,942 --> 00:24:54,196
So may all of you all be blessed.

171
00:24:54,785 --> 00:25:10,752
And now we'd like to ask Sister Chanda Siri to give us a few words, thank you.

172
00:25:11,615 --> 00:25:15,882
It's a very great privilege to be here today and I'm really enjoying

173
00:25:16,317 --> 00:25:21,285
the fact that there are so many of you and from so many different cultures and backgrounds.

174
00:25:22,445 --> 00:25:35,405
This is one of the most exciting things I think about Buddhism at this time, that it's drawing people who've grown up in a Buddhist culture and also many people who've been drawn by the teachings about suffering and about the ending of suffering.

175
00:25:35,555 --> 00:25:36,896
That's certainly what drew me.

176
00:25:37,238 --> 00:25:43,548
And I have to confess that I wasn't really very interested in devotional practices when I first became a nun.

177
00:25:44,250 --> 00:25:49,480
I loved the teachings, I loved the meditation, and I loved the possibility of liberation from suffering.

178
00:25:50,300 --> 00:25:52,585
And that certainly kept me going for a long time.

179
00:25:52,970 --> 00:25:58,019
However, Venerable Bodhidharma asked if I would say a few words about devotion this afternoon.

180
00:25:58,059 --> 00:26:07,619
And over the years, I've come to have a very strong sense of devotion myself and also to see the great value of this.

181
00:26:08,376 --> 00:26:12,982
the devotion has arisen out of a sense of having contemplated the life of the Buddha.

182
00:26:13,503 --> 00:26:22,175
I found actually, strangely enough, the biggest thing for me was actually learning about the Buddha's experience with the monks and nuns, and how the discipline was established.

183
00:26:22,455 --> 00:26:32,730
There are some very remarkable stories about the things that the monks and nuns got up to, and there's a real sense of appreciation of the Buddha's brilliance.

184
00:26:32,710 --> 00:26:43,423
in the way he established the order of the monastic community and the relationship between the lay community and the monastic community, he created a situation where many, many people could benefit.

185
00:26:44,625 --> 00:26:47,509
And that brought great joy to my heart when I contemplated that.

186
00:26:47,548 --> 00:26:54,076
I thought there's no way I could think up such a wonderful social system.

187
00:26:56,301 --> 00:27:11,374
Thinking about the benefits of devotion and why it's a wonderful occasion for us here together to be together, one of the things I realized as having grown up in a Western culture is that I have a very critical mind.

188
00:27:11,354 --> 00:27:14,460
And also I have quite a strong tendency to be an individual.

189
00:27:14,799 --> 00:27:19,188
I tend to think of myself as being rather special and rather important.

190
00:27:19,648 --> 00:27:26,441
And I can suffer enormously because of maybe not being quite good enough, not being quite special enough.

191
00:27:26,882 --> 00:27:29,666
There are all kinds of ways that I can cause myself suffering.

192
00:27:30,405 --> 00:27:37,693
These occasions for devotion invite us to go beyond that self-centeredness, self-preoccupation.

193
00:27:38,474 --> 00:27:53,612
They invite us to contemplate the possibility of liberation, the possibility of liberation from selfishness, from foolishness, to be lifted, to be carried by each other.

194
00:27:54,554 --> 00:28:06,326
when we perform the circumambulation of the stupa, when we chant the suttas, we join together in recollecting the teachings, in celebrating the fact of the Buddha and his enlightenment.

195
00:28:06,346 --> 00:28:08,729
And something happens in the heart.

196
00:28:08,808 --> 00:28:19,701
It's not a rational thing, but there's a sense of being nourished, a sense of joy can arise, a sense of letting go and just entering into something altogether.

197
00:28:20,692 --> 00:28:22,315
Spiritual training is not easy.

198
00:28:22,575 --> 00:28:31,165
Those of you who've come here for retreats, I'm sure have found it wonderful in the end, but I imagine that maybe the beginning, and certainly the middle, may have been quite difficult.

199
00:28:32,227 --> 00:28:48,928
And it's at times like that that these practices of devotion can really help us to go beyond, to recollect our possibility, our capacity for liberation, can keep us going, can keep us treading the path.

200
00:28:50,073 --> 00:29:13,194
So I encourage you to, and I'd really just like to celebrate the fact that we have this place here in Britain, a place that we can come to, that we can come and pay homage to the Buddha, the Dhamma, the Sangha, and contemplate the teachings, contemplate this possibility that each one of us has to free the heart from all suffering.

201
00:29:15,013 --> 00:29:43,338
It takes a bit of effort, it takes a lot of encouragement, but I would like to just encourage everybody to, having come here, maybe for the first time, maybe you've been coming for many, many years, just to keep coming, to keep treading the path, and may you all experience perfect liberation, may we all experience, may we all experience perfect liberation from all dukkha, which is what the Buddha has promised us that we are capable of.

202
00:29:43,358 --> 00:29:44,920
So let's not forget that.

203
00:29:44,900 --> 00:30:06,352
Can we have one or two volunteers just to hand these little presents out to the monks?

204
00:30:06,432 --> 00:30:08,935
One or two volunteers?

205
00:30:08,955 --> 00:30:11,380
Here, here, here.

206
00:30:16,792 --> 00:30:21,977
No, one of them.

207
00:30:44,688 --> 00:31:11,049
Thank you.

208
00:31:11,501 --> 00:31:35,208
Finally, I'd like to ask Dr Sita Sriwadana, who has been our chairman of the Trust since it was founded, to say a few words.

209
00:31:35,248 --> 00:31:38,471
You're going to turn it up.

210
00:31:39,093 --> 00:31:41,215
If you can't hear, please tell me.

211
00:31:41,236 --> 00:31:42,438
I'm going to try without the mic.

212
00:31:43,097 --> 00:31:43,479
Okay?

213
00:31:44,420 --> 00:31:49,807
Venerable sirs and friends in the Dhamma, it is with great pleasure and a sense of pride...

214
00:31:53,491 --> 00:32:02,525
It is with great pleasure and a sense of pride that I welcome you all here today on behalf of Bhante Bodhi Dhamma and all the trustees of the Satipanya Trust.

215
00:32:03,605 --> 00:32:07,310
I'd like to thank you all for joining us in this ceremony.

216
00:32:07,730 --> 00:32:17,684
We are especially happy that our two senior monks, Venerable and Venerable were able to come from Sri Lanka to officiate.

217
00:32:17,704 --> 00:32:28,621
And to Venerable head of the London Buddhist and to representatives and the nuns from and representatives of all other religious denominations here.

218
00:32:29,521 --> 00:32:30,303
Thank you all.

219
00:32:30,323 --> 00:32:31,424
A warm welcome.

220
00:32:32,029 --> 00:32:41,182
Even though this is a small spiritual enterprise, you would be surprised at the number of people who have been involved in the past 10 years since the Trust was founded.

221
00:32:42,003 --> 00:32:49,453
The list is so long, and for fear of favor, I shall only mention the three persons who were crucial to this day.

222
00:32:50,134 --> 00:32:55,201
Firstly, Roy Griffiths, who did all the groundwork and set up the statue of Pond Yin.

223
00:32:55,642 --> 00:32:58,205
I wonder if I can ask you to raise your hand, Roy?

224
00:32:58,996 --> 00:33:04,269
Well, he's disappeared.

225
00:33:05,792 --> 00:33:09,804
Then there's Gary Higgins, a master stonemason who built the stupor.

226
00:33:09,824 --> 00:33:11,587
Can you raise your hand, Gary?

227
00:33:15,652 --> 00:33:20,046
Archie Kennedy, who fashioned the reliquary but was unable to be here today.

228
00:33:20,768 --> 00:33:26,064
In our custom, we say thank you by joining our hands together and saying sadhu three times.

229
00:33:26,085 --> 00:33:27,769
Can we say sadhu?

230
00:33:28,833 --> 00:33:28,993
Sadhu.

231
00:33:29,675 --> 00:33:29,796
Sadhu.

232
00:33:30,821 --> 00:33:37,088
We have progressed a great deal from our small beginnings in April 2007, when this property was purchased.

233
00:33:37,809 --> 00:33:40,252
It has been extensively repaired and upgraded.

234
00:33:40,813 --> 00:33:54,888
On 30 June 2007, the formal opening ceremony of this retreat took place, which was attended by senior Buddhist monks from Sri Lanka and London, by well-wishers, by supporters and members of the local community.

235
00:33:55,342 --> 00:33:57,704
Retreats have been conducted here from that time.

236
00:33:58,486 --> 00:34:02,349
The retreat program is open to all, including the general public.

237
00:34:02,951 --> 00:34:08,036
Its aim is to integrate Vipassana meditation practice into ordinary daily life.

238
00:34:08,797 --> 00:34:10,320
Don't worry, it's only another page.

239
00:34:17,268 --> 00:34:24,657
There are also opportunities to study Buddhism and to benefit from periods of calm, reflection and contemplation.

240
00:34:25,244 --> 00:34:29,731
Further opportunities are available to test the monastic life for both men and women.

241
00:34:30,353 --> 00:34:35,382
We have already had three men who have experienced this and I believe two women are next to do so.

242
00:34:36,463 --> 00:34:41,974
Today marks the culmination of the construction of the stupa by placing the reliquary on it.

243
00:34:42,614 --> 00:34:45,699
The stupa varies slightly in shape in different countries of the world.

244
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:46,661
I think the

245
00:34:47,164 --> 00:34:47,806
Rev.

246
00:34:48,126 --> 00:34:50,329
Piyananda is trying to explain to you about that.

247
00:34:50,471 --> 00:34:53,876
But the basic form is based on an inverted bowl.

248
00:34:53,896 --> 00:34:58,083
This stupa is built of Welsh slate in keeping with the surroundings.

249
00:34:58,103 --> 00:35:09,222
Stupas house Buddhist relics and that is why we are here today to place a reliquary which has the Buddhist relics and a DVD of all the Buddhist scriptures on the stupa and thus complete it.

250
00:35:10,047 --> 00:35:17,619
We are pleased to have done all this work in four years, and I invite all of you to make more use of this center in such peaceful surroundings.

251
00:35:18,480 --> 00:35:28,755
Our future plans are to make the center accessible to wheelchair users, and at the same time, extend the area for walking meditation, and also provide space for formal retreatants.

252
00:35:29,396 --> 00:35:32,240
We appeal to you to help us with this project.

253
00:35:32,221 --> 00:35:35,826
Finally, I hope you have all had a peaceful and uplifting day.

254
00:35:36,306 --> 00:35:42,255
On behalf of Bhante and the trustees, I wish you all a long and healthy life and a safe journey home.

255
00:35:42,414 --> 00:35:42,835
Thank you.

256
00:35:51,246 --> 00:35:53,990
It's now 3.45 and it's time for tea.

257
00:35:56,914 --> 00:36:00,760
Thank you all for coming.

258
00:36:04,385 --> 00:36:32,788
Thank you.

